var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"type_condition/#Initial-and-boundary-conditions","page":"Condition","title":"Initial and boundary conditions","text":"To launch a simulation, initial and boundary conditions are necessary.","category":"section"},{"location":"type_condition/#Initial-conditions","page":"Condition","title":"Initial conditions","text":"The types of initial conditions are abstracted as \n\nCurrently, available options are","category":"section"},{"location":"type_condition/#Boundary-conditions","page":"Condition","title":"Boundary conditions","text":"The type of the boundary conditions is determined by \n\nCurrently, available options are\n\nWith these types of boundary conditions, \n\ncan be constructed. There are two types of the boundary.","category":"section"},{"location":"type_condition/#Domain-boundary","page":"Condition","title":"Domain boundary","text":"KitAMR.jl always adopts square simulation domain. At the edges of the domain, proper conditions are required to maintain the well-posedness.","category":"section"},{"location":"type_condition/#Immersed-boundary","page":"Condition","title":"Immersed boundary","text":"KitAMR.jl adopts the immersed boundary method (IBM) to resolve boundaries with complex geometry. To define the geometry, KitAMR.jl provides following interface.\n\nAs the special case, the cirlce in 2D and sphere in 3D are defined separately, and are abstracted as AbstractCircle=Union{Circle,Sphere}.\n\nFor other cases, KitAMR.jl read .csv file for 2D, which defines the vertices coordinates of the closed boundary curve; and .stl file for 3D, which provides the triangular discretization of the boundary surface. The example can be find in /example/airfoil and /example/X38 respectively.\n\nThe most common constructor is\n\nThe most common constructor is\n\nTriangleKDT is a struct containing information related to K-D tree for efficient mesh generation:","category":"section"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.AbstractInitCondType","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.AbstractInitCondType","text":"abstract type AbstractInitCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Uniform","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Uniform","text":"struct Uniform <: AbstractInitCondType\n\nUniform initial condition. The field will be initialized with the Maxwellian distribution determined by the unified primary macroscopic variables in ic.\n\nFields\n\nic::AbstractVector\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.PCoordFn","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.PCoordFn","text":"struct PCoordFn <: AbstractInitCondType\n\nPhysical-coordinates-determined initial condition. The field will be initialized with the Maxwellian distribution determined by the user-defined-function in PCIC_fn. The function will return primary macroscopic variables vector according to the information of the physical grid (mostly the physical coordinates).\n\nFields\n\nPCIC_fn::Function\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.AbstractBoundCondType","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.AbstractBoundCondType","text":"abstract type AbstractBoundCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Maxwellian","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Maxwellian","text":"abstract type Maxwellian <: AbstractBoundCondType\n\nFully diffused Maxwellian gas-surface interaction model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.SuperSonicInflow","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.SuperSonicInflow","text":"abstract type SuperSonicInflow <: AbstractBoundCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.SuperSonicOutflow","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.SuperSonicOutflow","text":"abstract type SuperSonicOutflow <: AbstractBoundCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.UniformOutflow","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.UniformOutflow","text":"abstract type UniformOutflow <: AbstractBoundCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.InterpolatedOutflow","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.InterpolatedOutflow","text":"abstract type InterpolatedOutflow <: AbstractBoundCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Period","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Period","text":"abstract type Period <: AbstractBoundCondType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.AbstractBoundaryType","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.AbstractBoundaryType","text":"abstract type AbstractBoundaryType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Domain","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Domain","text":"struct Domain{T<:AbstractBoundCondType} <: AbstractBoundaryType\n\nStructure of domain boundary.\n\nFields\n\nid::Int64: Index of the domain boundary. From 1 to 6, it represents the boundary of xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax, zmin, zmax.\nrefine::Bool: Whether refine at the domain boundary. Default is false.\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}: The boundary condition at the domain boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Circle","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Circle","text":"struct Circle{T<:AbstractBoundCondType} <: AbstractBoundaryType\n\ncenter::Vector: Center of the circle.\nradius::Real: Radius of the circle.\nsolid::Bool: Is solid inside the circle?\nsearch_coeffi::Real: Refinement coefficient.\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}: Primary macroscopic variables of the solid.\nsearch_radius::Real: Maximum distance of the refinement region from the boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Sphere","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Sphere","text":"struct Sphere{T<:AbstractBoundCondType} <: AbstractBoundaryType\n\ncenter::Vector\nradius::Real\nsolid::Bool\nsearch_coeffi::Real\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}\nsearch_radius::Real\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Vertices","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Vertices","text":"struct Vertices{DIM, T<:AbstractBoundCondType} <: AbstractBoundaryType\n\nvertices::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: Vertices of the boundary, sorted in clockwise or counterclockwise order.\nsolid::Bool\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}\nbox::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: The outer box of the vertices as [[xmin,ymin,zmin],[xmax,ymax,zmax]].\nsearch_radius::Real: The number of cell layers refined from the boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Vertices-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Type{T}, String, Any, Any, Any}} where T<:AbstractBoundCondType","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Vertices","text":"Vertices(\n    _::Type{T<:AbstractBoundCondType},\n    file::String,\n    solid,\n    refine_coeffi,\n    bc\n) -> Vertices\n\n\nfile is the path to the .csv file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Triangles","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Triangles","text":"struct Triangles{T<:AbstractBoundCondType} <: AbstractBoundaryType\n\nsolid::Bool\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}\nsearch_radius::Real\ntkdt::TriangleKDT\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Triangles-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Type{T}, String, Any, Any, Any}} where T<:AbstractBoundCondType","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.Triangles","text":"Triangles(\n    _::Type{T<:AbstractBoundCondType},\n    file::String,\n    solid,\n    search_radius,\n    bc\n) -> Triangles\n\n\nfile is the path to the .stl file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.TriangleKDT","page":"Condition","title":"KitAMR.TriangleKDT","text":"struct TriangleKDT\n\nkdt::NearestNeighbors.KDTree\nmesh::GeometryBasics.Mesh\ntable::Vector{NearestNeighbors.HyperRectangle{StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, Float64}}}\ntriangle_recs::Vector{NearestNeighbors.HyperRectangle{StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, Float64}}}\ntriangle_edges::Vector{Vector{StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, Float64}}}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_velocity_space/#Velocity-space","page":"Velocity space","title":"Velocity space","text":"In kinetic methods, variables are also discretized in velocity space. Information in velocity space are separately stored in AbstractPsData, and are organized as following.","category":"section"},{"location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.AbstractVsData","page":"Velocity space","title":"KitAMR.AbstractVsData","text":"abstract type AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.VS_Data","page":"Velocity space","title":"KitAMR.VS_Data","text":"mutable struct VS_Data{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nvs_num::Int64: Number of velocity cells.\nlevel::Vector{Int8}: Refinement level of velocity cells.\nweight::Vector{Float64}: Quadrature weight of velocity cells.\nmidpoint::Matrix{Float64}: Coordinates of centers of velocity cells in velocity space.\ndf::Matrix{Float64}: Discretized distribution function.\nsdf::Array{Float64, 3}: Spatial gradients (df/dx) of distribution function.\nflux::Matrix{Float64}: Numerical flux of distribution function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.Ghost_VS_Data","page":"Velocity space","title":"KitAMR.Ghost_VS_Data","text":"mutable struct Ghost_VS_Data{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nvs_num::Int64\nlevel::Vector{Int8}\nweight::Vector{Float64}\nmidpoint::Matrix{Float64}\ndf::Matrix{Float64}\nsdf::Array{Float64, 3}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.Face_VS_Data","page":"Velocity space","title":"KitAMR.Face_VS_Data","text":"struct Face_VS_Data{DIM, NDF}\n\nInformation of the velocity space corresponding to the face during the calculation of numerical flux.\n\nheavi::Vector{Bool}: Upwinding flags. Upwinding velocities are set to true.\nweight::AbstractVector{Float64}\nmidpoint::AbstractMatrix{Float64}\nvn::AbstractVector{Float64}: Normal component of velocities across the face.\ndf::AbstractMatrix{Float64}\nsdf::AbstractArray{Float64}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.CuttedVelocityCells","page":"Velocity space","title":"KitAMR.CuttedVelocityCells","text":"mutable struct CuttedVelocityCells\n\nStructure for cut cell in velocity space used in immersed boundaries.\n\nindices::Vector{Int64}: Indices of cut cells in SolidNeighbor's VS_Data.\nweight::Vector{Float64}: Quadrature weight of velocity cells. Specially, the weight of cut cells is set to 0.\ngas_dfs::Matrix{Float64}: Distribution function of gas part corresponding to velocity at the center of cut cells.\nsolid_dfs::Matrix{Float64}: Distribution function of solid part corresponding to velocity at the center of cut cells.\ngas_weights::Vector{Float64}: Areas of gas part in cut cells.\nsolid_weights::Vector{Float64}: Areas of solid part in cut cells.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#Physical-space","page":"Physical space","title":"Physical space","text":"Information in physical space are organized as following.\n\nTo calculate the numerical flux, the mapping between cells and faces are required, which is defined by","category":"section"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.AbstractPsData","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.AbstractPsData","text":"abstract type AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.PS_Data","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.PS_Data","text":"mutable struct PS_Data{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nquadid::Int32: Index of the quadrant corresponding to PS_Data.\nbound_enc::Int64: Encoding of the cell type. 0:fluid cell;>0: donor cell of bound_enc th immersed boundary;<0: solid cell (or solid neighbor) of bound_enc th boundary.\nsolid_cell_index::Vector{Int64}: Deprecated.\nds::Vector{Float64}: Faces area (length).\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}: Coordinates of the cell center.\nqf::Vector{Float64}: Heat flux.\nw::Vector{Float64}: Conserved variables.\nsw::Matrix{Float64}: Gradients of conserved variables.\nprim::Vector{Float64}: Primary variables.\nflux::Vector{Float64}: Conserved flux.\nvs_data::VS_Data: Data of the velocity space.\nneighbor::Neighbor: Neighbor of the cell.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.Ghost_PS_Data","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.Ghost_PS_Data","text":"mutable struct Ghost_PS_Data{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nowner_rank::Int64\nquadid::Int64\nbound_enc::Int64\nds::Vector{Float64}\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}\nw::Vector{Float64}\nsw::Matrix{Float64}\nvs_data::Ghost_VS_Data\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.InsideSolidData","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.InsideSolidData","text":"mutable struct InsideSolidData{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.GhostInsideSolidData","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.GhostInsideSolidData","text":"mutable struct GhostInsideSolidData{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.Neighbor","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.Neighbor","text":"mutable struct Neighbor{DIM, NDF}\n\ndata::Array{Array{Union{Nothing, AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}}, 1}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}\nstate::Vector{Int64}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.SolidNeighbor","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.SolidNeighbor","text":"mutable struct SolidNeighbor{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nbound_enc::Int64\nfaceid::Int64: Index of the face of the donor cell corresponding to this SolidNeighbor.\nav_id::Int64: Deprecated.\naux_point::Vector{Float64}: Intersect point at the boundary corresponding to this SolidNeighbor.\nnormal::Vector{Float64}: Normal vector of the boundary at aux_point.\nsolid_cell::AbstractPsData: Solid_cell corresponding to this SolidNeighbor.\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}\nds::Vector{Float64}\nw::Vector{Float64}\nsw::Matrix{Float64}\ncvc::CuttedVelocityCells: Struct containing information of cut cell in velocity space.\nvs_data::VS_Data\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.AbstractFace","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.AbstractFace","text":"abstract type AbstractFace\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.DomainFace","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.DomainFace","text":"struct DomainFace{DIM, NDF, T} <: KitAMR.BoundaryFace\n\nFace at the domain edge.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.FullFace","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.FullFace","text":"struct FullFace{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.InnerFace\n\nFace shared by cells with the same refinement level.\n\nrot::Float64: Rotational coefficient of the face. -1 if here_data locates at the negative direction relative to the face.\ndirection::Int64: Direction of the face's normal. 1, 2, 3 correspond to x, y, z respectively.\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}: Coordinates of the face's center.\nhere_data::PS_Data: PS_Data on one side of the face. It is guaranteed to be local.\nthere_data::AbstractPsData: AbstractPsData on the other side of the face. It can be a ghost one.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.HangingFace","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.HangingFace","text":"struct HangingFace{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.InnerFace\n\nFaces shared by cells with different refinement levels. The cell with lower level is local.\n\nrot::Float64\ndirection::Int64\nmidpoint::Vector{Vector{Float64}}\nhere_data::PS_Data\nthere_data::Array{AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}: AbstractPsDatas with higher refinement level.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.BackHangingFace","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.BackHangingFace","text":"struct BackHangingFace{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.InnerFace\n\nFaces shared by cells with different refinement levels. The cell with lower level is ghost.\n\nrot::Float64\ndirection::Int64\nmidpoint::Vector{Vector{Float64}}\nhere_data::Array{PS_Data{DIM, NDF}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}\nthere_data::AbstractPsData\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.FluxData","page":"Physical space","title":"KitAMR.FluxData","text":"struct FluxData{T<:KitAMR.InnerFace}\n\nStruct for flux calculation corresponding to a single face.\n\nrot::Float64\ndirection::Int64\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}\nhere_data::AbstractPsData\nthere_data::AbstractPsData\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"methods_finalize/#Finalization","page":"Finalization","title":"Finalization","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"methods_finalize/#KitAMR.finalize!","page":"Finalization","title":"KitAMR.finalize!","text":"finalize!(\n    ps4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    amr::KitAMR_Data\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nfinalize!(\n    ps4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est},\n    amr::KitAMR_Data\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"methods_finalize/#KitAMR.residual_check!","page":"Finalization","title":"KitAMR.residual_check!","text":"residual_check!(\n    ps_data::PS_Data,\n    prim::Vector{Float64},\n    global_data::Global_Data\n)\n\n\nUpdate residuals.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"type_output/#Output-configuration","page":"Output","title":"Output configuration","text":"KitAMR.jl outputs the field as .jld2 and .pvtu files for post-processing.\n\nSupported vtk cell types are\n\nNote that the vertices in .pvtu file are redundant. To obtain contour of the field, a cleaning process in post-process software is required. For example, using Paraview, one needs to execute Clean to Grid before contour.\n\nTriangle and Tetra are chosen for smoother field visualization, but will not improve the accuracy of the solution. The variables on their vertices are linearly reconstructed. ","category":"section"},{"location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Output","page":"Output","title":"KitAMR.Output","text":"mutable struct Output\n\nStructure of output information.\n\nFields\n\nvtk_celltype::DataType: VTK cell type in physical space. Available options: Pixel and Triangle for 2D; Voxel and Tetra for 3D.\nvs_vtk_celltype::DataType: VTK cell type in velocity space. Available options: Pixel for 2D.\nanim_dt::Float64: Time interval between animation frames.\nvs_output_criterion::Function: User-defined-function determining the physical cells need to output the velocity space.\nanim_index::Int64: Index of the last saved animation frame.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Pixel","page":"Output","title":"KitAMR.Pixel","text":"abstract type Pixel <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Voxel","page":"Output","title":"KitAMR.Voxel","text":"abstract type Voxel <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Triangle","page":"Output","title":"KitAMR.Triangle","text":"abstract type Triangle <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Tetra","page":"Output","title":"KitAMR.Tetra","text":"abstract type Tetra <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_configure/#Configuration","page":"Configuration","title":"Configuration","text":"To simulate a problem using KitAMR, user is required to define the problem. Most of the user-provided information is collected in Configure struct. ","category":"section"},{"location":"type_configure/#KitAMR.Configure","page":"Configuration","title":"KitAMR.Configure","text":"struct Configure{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of problem configuration. DIM and NDF represent the dimension number of the problem and the number of the distribution function. This struct plays an key role in the solution process.\n\nFields\n\ngeometry::Vector{Float64}: Range of the simulated domain. As an example, for 2D case, it should be aligned as [xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax].\ntrees_num::Vector{Int64}: Number of tree roots for each dimension. For 2D case, it should be aligned as [xnum,ynum]\nquadrature::Union{KitAMR.AbstractQuadrature, Vector{Float64}}: For Vector type, it represents the range of the velocity space. For 2D case, it should be aligned as [umin,umax,vmin,vmax]. The AbstractQuadrature type is reserved for other quadrature rule like Gauss-Hermite.\nvs_trees_num::Vector{Int64}: Number of tree roots for each dimension in velocity space.\nIC::AbstractInitCondType: Initial condition defined by AbstractInitCondType.\ndomain::Vector{Domain}: Types of the domain boundary. For 2D case, the vector should catain 4 elements corresponding to the 4 domain boundaries. The element type is defined by Domain.\nIB::Vector{AbstractBoundaryType}: Immersed boundary. Multiple boundaries are supported. The element type is defined by AbstractBoundaryType\ngas::Gas: Properties of the simulated gas defined by Gas.\nsolver::Solver: Setup of the solver defined by Solver.\noutput::Output: Setup of the output form defined by Output.\nuser_defined::KitAMR.UDF: Functions defined by users, including some criteria.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_configure/#KitAMR.Solver","page":"Configuration","title":"KitAMR.Solver","text":"struct Solver\n\nStructure of solver configuration.\n\nFields\n\nCFL::Float64: Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy number.\nAMR_PS_MAXLEVEL::Int64: Maximum level of the (static) AMR in physical space.\nAMR_DYNAMIC_PS_MAXLEVEL::Int64: Maximum level of the dynamic AMR in physical space. In most cases, it should be smaller than the static one. The default is equal to AMR_PS_MAXLEVEL.\nAMR_VS_MAXLEVEL::Int64: Maximum level of the AMR in velocity space.\nflux::KitAMR.AbstractFluxType: The numerical flux type.\ntime_marching::KitAMR.AbstractTimeMarchingType: The time-marching scheme.\nPS_DYNAMIC_AMR::Bool: The dynamic AMR in physical space is open or not. The default is true.\nVS_DYNAMIC_AMR::Bool: The dynamic AMR in velocity space is open or not. The default is true.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#Data","page":"Data","title":"Data","text":"All of the datas in KitAMR.jl are organized as follows:","category":"section"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.KitAMR_Data","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.KitAMR_Data","text":"mutable struct KitAMR_Data{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure that collects all of the data.\n\nglobal_data::Global_Data\nghost::Ghost\nfield::Field\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Global_Data","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Global_Data","text":"mutable struct Global_Data{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of required information during a simulation.\n\nconfig::Configure: Defined by Configure.\nforest::Forest: Defined by Forest.\nstatus::Status: Defined by Status.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Forest","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Forest","text":"mutable struct Forest{DIM}\n\nStructure related to p4est.\n\np4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}}\nghost::Union{Ptr{p4est_ghost_t}, Ptr{p8est_ghost_t}}\nmesh::Union{Ptr{p4est_mesh_t}, Ptr{p8est_mesh_t}}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Status","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Status","text":"mutable struct Status\n\nStructure of simulation status. It contains the real time information, and is updated every step.\n\nFields\n\nmax_vs_num::Int64: Maximum number of the velocity grids among ghost quadrants.\ngradmax::Vector{Float64}: Maximum absolute value of the gradients of conserved variables.\nwmax::Vector{Float64}: Maximum value of conserved variables.\nwmin::Vector{Float64}: Minimum value of conserved variables.\nΔt::Float64: Time step size used in iterate!.\nΔt_ξ::Float64: Time step size constraint by grid size.\nsim_time::Float64: Dimensionless simulation time.\nps_adapt_step::Int64: Number of steps after last AMR in physical space.\nvs_adapt_step::Int64: Number of steps after last AMR in velocity space.\npartition_step::Int64: Number of steps after last partition.\nresidual::Residual: Residual of conserved variables defined by Residual.\nsave_flag::Base.RefValue{Bool}: Flag indicating whether to save.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Residual","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Residual","text":"mutable struct Residual\n\nstep::Int64: Current step number.\nresidual::Vector{Float64}: Residual of primary variables, is updated by residual_check!.\nsumRes::Vector{Float64}: Summation of residuals.\nsumAvg::Vector{Float64}: Summation of primary variables to average sumRes.\nredundant_step::Int64: Count of redundant step to insure the convergence.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Ghost","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Ghost","text":"mutable struct Ghost\n\nStructure of ghost layer for communication between processors.\n\nghost_exchange::Ghost_Exchange\nghost_wrap::Vector{KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData}\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Ghost_Exchange","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Ghost_Exchange","text":"mutable struct Ghost_Exchange\n\nStructure of ghost data and pointers used by p4est.\n\nghost_datas::Any\nghost_slopes::Any\nghost_structures::Any\nmirror_data_pointers::Any\nmirror_slope_pointers::Any\nmirror_structure_pointers::Any\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Field","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.Field","text":"mutable struct Field{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of fields data.\n\ntrees::PS_Trees: Cells data defined by PS_Trees.\nfaces::Vector{AbstractFace}: Mapping between faces and cells. The element type is defined by AbstractFace.\nimmersed_boundary::KitAMR.ImmersedBoundary\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_data/#KitAMR.PS_Trees","page":"Data","title":"KitAMR.PS_Trees","text":"mutable struct PS_Trees{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of cells data managed by Julia.\n\ndata::Array{Array{AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}, 1}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}\noffset::Int64: Offset of treeid used in partition.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"type_gas/#Gas-properties","page":"Gas","title":"Gas properties","text":"Struct that determines the properties of the simulated gas.","category":"section"},{"location":"type_gas/#KitAMR.Gas","page":"Gas","title":"KitAMR.Gas","text":"mutable struct Gas <: KitAMR.AbstractGas\n\nKn::Float64: Default: 0.05\nPr::Float64: Default: 2 / 3\nK::Float64: The translational internal DOF. Default: 1.0\nγ::Float64: Default: 5 / 3\nω::Float64: Default: 0.5\nαᵣ::Float64: Default: 1.0\nωᵣ::Float64: Default: 0.81\nμᵣ::Float64: The reference viscosity. Default: refvhsvis(Kn, αᵣ, ωᵣ)\nT_ref::Float64: The reference temperature of the molecular model. Default: 1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#KitAMR.jl","page":"Home","title":"KitAMR.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Motivation","page":"Home","title":"Motivation","text":"KitAMR.jl is a distributed adaptive Cartesian grid solver for kinetic equations, developed based on P4est.jl. Its goal is to achieve large-scale parallel solving of 2D and 3D flows across all regimes, leveraging GPUs, differentiable programming, and machine learning to enhance solving efficiency.\n\nFor 1.0 version, we enable the solver to determinately simulate rarefied flows with high efficiency. The following functionalities have been implemented:\n\nPhysical mesh generation for arbitrary boundary geometry;\nImmersed boundary method for Maxwellian gas-surface interaction model;\nGeometric adaptation of physical space grids;\nDynamic adaptation of physical space grids;\nDynamic adaptation of velocity space grids;\nDistributed parallelism on CPUs;\nLoad balancing based on phase space grid density;\nLinear reconstruction with second-order spatial accuracy;\nComposite Newton-Cotes rule with second-order quadrature accuracy;\nVTK&JLD output for post-processing.\n\nAll of the funcationalities are applicable to both 2D and 3D cases.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Theory","page":"Home","title":"Theory","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Kinetic-Methods","page":"Home","title":"Kinetic Methods","text":"In kinetic theory, methods simulate the macroscopic motion of fluids by describing the evolution of distribution functions of fluid particles in velocity space over time. Such methods include direct simulation Monte Carlo (DSMC), discrete velocity method (DVM), lattice Boltzmann equation (LBE), gas-kinetic scheme, semi-Lagrangian method, implicit-explicit (IMEX) method, and others.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Distribution-Function","page":"Home","title":"Distribution Function","text":"In kinetic methods, the state of the fluid is described by a distribution function f(mathbfxmathbfut). The distribution function represents the number of particles at a given moment in time at a specific physical space point in a particular velocity space element. Its normalization property is\n\nrho(mathbfxt)=iiint_-infty^inftyf(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\n\n, where rho(mathbfxt) is the density of flows at mathbfx in time t. At higher temperatures, molecular internal degrees of freedom are excited, and the distribution function will depend on these degrees of freedom as well. For simplicity, we do not currently consider this situation.\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"assets/distribution.jpg\" alt=\"Image 1\" width=\"300\" style=\"margin-right: 1px;\">\n    <figcaption><i>The distribution function in 2D velocity space.</i></figcaption>\n</div>\n\nWith the distribution function, macroscopic conservative variables can be caculated as follows:\n\nbeginsplit\nrho = iiint_-infty^inftyf(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nrhomathbf U = iiint_-infty^inftymathbf uf(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nrho E = iiint_-infty^infty frac 12 mathbf u^2f(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nmathbf q=iiint_-infty^infty mathbf ufrac 12 mathbf u^2f(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nendsplit","category":"section"},{"location":"#Boltzmann-Equation","page":"Home","title":"Boltzmann Equation","text":"The evolution of the distribution function follows the Boltzmann equation.\n\nfracpartial fpartial t+mathbfucdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfx+mathbfFcdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfu=iiint_-infty^inftyint_0^4pi(f^*f_1^*-ff_1)c_rsigma dOmega dc_1\n\nThe Boltzmann equation holds a central position in kinetic theory, which is an integro-differential equation, with a four-fold integral term on the right-hand side. The complexity introduced by this term makes solving the Boltzmann equation challenging. Therefore, as a simplification, kinetic methods often solve its model equations instead.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Shakhov-Model-Equation","page":"Home","title":"Shakhov Model Equation","text":"The simplified equation obtained after simplifying the collision term is known as the Shakhov model equation:\n\nbegincases\nfracpartial fpartial t+mathbfucdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfx+mathbfFcdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfu=fracg^+-ftau\ng^+=g1+frac45(1-mathrmPr)lambda^2fracmathbfucdotmathbfqrho(2lambda mathbfu^2-5)\nendcases\n\n, Where mathrm Pr is the Prandtl number, mathbfq is the heat flux, and tau is the relaxation time typically given through phenomenological models to match experimental data. The Shakhov model can provide results close to the Boltzmann equation for mass, momentum, energy, and heat fluxes in situations where flow velocities are not very high and deviations from equilibrium are not very large. And the current solver is based on Shakhov model.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Computing-Methods","page":"Home","title":"Computing Methods","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Finite-Volume-Method-(FVM)","page":"Home","title":"Finite Volume Method (FVM)","text":"The underlying discretization of the Boltzmann equation is based on finite volume method, with its discrete form as follows:\n\noverline U_jOmega_j^n+1 = \noverline U_j Omega_j^n-Delta tsum_partialOmegamathbfF^*cdotDeltamathbfS+Delta t overlineQ_jOmega_j\n\n, where overline U_j^ncoloneqqfrac1Omega_jint_Omega_jUdOmega_j^n, overline Q_j^ncoloneqqfrac1Omega_jint_Omega_jQdOmega_j are the cell-averaged conservative variable and source. And overline Q_j^* and mathbfF^* are respectively cell- and time-averaged sources and numerical flux, which are defined as overline Q_j^*coloneqqfrac1Delta tint_n^n+1overline Q_jdt and mathbf F^*cdot Delta mathbfScoloneqq frac1Delta tint_n^n+1mathbf FcdotDelta mathbfSdt. It is an exact relation for the time evolution of the space averaged conservative avriables over cell j from time step n to n+1. And the numerical flux mathbf F^* identifies completely a scheme by the way it approximates the time-averaged physical flux along each cell face.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Numerical-Flux","page":"Home","title":"Numerical Flux","text":"Currently the best supported numerical flux is the semi-implicit DVM, with interface variables obtained from linear reconsitruction with the VanLeer limiter. For specific implementation details, please refer to the relevant literature.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Discrete-Velocity-Method","page":"Home","title":"Discrete Velocity Method","text":"DVM is one of the popular approaches for solving rarefied flow problems. In this method, the particle velocity space is discretized into a finite set of points and the numerical quadrature rule is utilized to approximate the integration of moments. Since the particle velocity space is discretized into a finite set of points, the continuum Boltzmann equation is reduced to the corresponding discrete velocity Boltzmann equation (DVBE). Based on the original DVM, great variety of algorithms have been developed, including unified gas-kinetic scheme (UGKS), discrete unified gas-kinetic scheme (DUGKS), semi-Lagrangian method, etc. Most of the above methods can be applied from free molecular regime to continuum regime. But in order to make the quadrature error to be small enough, a large number of discrete velocity points are usually required. In particular, for fluid flows near continuum regime, the computational cost of DVM is much larger than those traditional CFD methods based on the Navier-Stokes equation.","category":"section"},{"location":"#Adaptive-Mesh-Refinement-(AMR)","page":"Home","title":"Adaptive Mesh Refinement (AMR)","text":"Considering the above limitation of DVM, we adopt Adaptive Mesh Refinement (AMR) to improve solving efficiency. AMR reallocates computational resources based on flow features, balancing efficiency and accuracy. \n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"assets/KitAMR.gif\" alt=\"Image 1\" width = \"600\" style=\"margin-left: 1px;\">\n    <figcaption><i>Hypersonic rarefied flow over a cylinder. The simultaneous AMR in physical space (left) and velocity space (right) are performed.</i></figcaption>\n</div>\n\nThe current solver discretizes with tree-based Cartesian grids, adapting the mesh in both physical and velocity space simultaneously, according to characteristics like conserved variables' gradients and the mass and energy proportion at the velocity collocations. Users can also customize the criteria for grid refinement or coarsening according to their own needs.\n\nFor an AMR solver, the load-balance ability is crucial for high efficiency. KitAMR.jl inherits the load-balance functionality in p4est. The domain decomposition is performed in physical space. The physical grids are encoded into a 1-dimensional sequence by Morton code, and are partitioned to maintain the phase grids number on each processor approximately equal.\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"assets/KitAMR_partition.gif\" alt=\"Image 1\" width = \"600\" style=\"margin-left: 1px;\">\n    <figcaption><i>The variation of the processor rank in physical domain during a simulation.</i></figcaption>\n</div>","category":"section"},{"location":"#Cartesian-Grids","page":"Home","title":"Cartesian Grids","text":"Cartesian grids offer advantages such as high grid quality, automated mesh generation, nature of the parallelism and capability for dynamic adaptation, but struggle with complex boundary geometries. To address this challenge, we developed an Immersed Boundary Method (IBM) for the discrete velocity model of the Boltzmann equation, which has been planted in KitAMR.jl. For more details, you may refer to our paper: https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2512.20252.","category":"section"},{"location":"methods_iterate/#Iteration","page":"Iteration","title":"Iteration","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"methods_iterate/#KitAMR.iterate!","page":"Iteration","title":"KitAMR.iterate!","text":"iterate!(amr::KitAMR_Data) -> Float64\n\n\nCollision and time marching.\n\n\n\n\n\niterate!(_::KitAMR.CAIDVM_Marching, amr::KitAMR_Data)\n\n\nIteration for Conserved Adaptive Implicit DVM (CAIDVM).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"}]
}
